  "prompt": "Does cctv works during power cut?",
  "response": "Whether or not CCTV works during a power cut depends on how it's set up. Here's a breakdown:\n\n**CCTV Systems That Likely WON'T Work During a Power Cut:**\n\n*   **Systems that rely solely on mains power:** If your CCTV cameras and recording equipment (like a DVR/NVR) are directly plugged into wall outlets and have no battery backup, they will stop working immediately when the power goes out.\n\n**CCTV Systems That MIGHT Work During a Power Cut:**\n\n*   **CCTV systems with battery backup:** Some CCTV systems are equipped with uninterruptible power supplies (UPS) or battery backups. These devices provide power to the cameras and recording equipment for a limited time after a power outage. The duration of the backup depends on the battery capacity and the power consumption of the system.\n*   **IP cameras with Power over Ethernet (PoE) and a UPS:** If your IP cameras are powered via PoE (Power over Ethernet) through a PoE switch, and the PoE switch is connected to a UPS, the cameras can continue to function during a power outage, as long as the network and the recording server also have power.\n*   **Wireless cameras with battery power:** Some wireless security cameras are powered by batteries. These will continue to record as long as the batteries have power. However, if they record to a device that does not have backup power, the recordings will be lost.\n\n**Important Considerations:**\n\n*   **Recording Equipment:** It's not enough for the cameras to have power. The DVR/NVR (or whatever device is storing the video) *also* needs power (either from a UPS or its own battery) to continue recording.\n*   **Network Infrastructure:** For IP-based systems, the router, modem, and any switches need to have power as well. If your internet goes down, you might still record locally, but you won't have remote access or cloud storage.\n*   **Length of Backup:** Battery backups are not indefinite. They are designed to provide power for a limited time, ranging from a few minutes to several hours, depending on the system.\n*   **Configuration:** Some systems may need to be specifically configured to record to local storage if the internet connection is lost.\n\n**How to Check If Your System Will Work During a Power Outage:**\n\n1.  **Look for UPS or Battery Backup:** Check if your DVR/NVR, cameras, or PoE switch are plugged into a UPS (Uninterruptible Power Supply) or have built-in batteries.\n2.  **Test It:** The best way is to safely unplug your system from the mains power (do this when you can easily restore power). See if the cameras continue to record. Check how long they last before shutting down.\n3.  **Review Your System's Documentation:** Your CCTV system's manual should provide information about its power requirements and whether it supports battery backup or UPS compatibility.\n\n**In summary:** CCTV systems *can* work during a power outage if they have a battery backup or are connected to a UPS. If your system relies solely on mains power, it will likely stop working. It's important to check your system's configuration and documentation to determine its capabilities.\n",
